04693nam a22005415i 9780822391050DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223910507 a10.1515/97808223910502doi  a(DE-B1597)553733  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0410102bisacsh1 aMcGillivray, Gillian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlazing Cane :bSugar Communities, Class, and State Formation in Cuba, 1868-1959 /cGillian McGillivray; Emily S. Rosenberg, Gilbert M. Joseph. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (414 p.) :b35 photographs, 3 tables, 3 maps, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions00tFrontmatter -- tAbout the Series -- tContents -- tPreface & Acknowledgments -- tChronology of Major Political Events -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one. The Colonial Compact, 1500-1895 -- tChapter two. Revolutionary Destruction of the Colonial Compact, 1895-98 -- tChapter three. U.S. Power and Cuban Middlemen, 1898-1917 -- tChapter four. The Patrons' Compact: "Peace," "Progress," and General Menocal, 1899-1919 -- tChapter five. Patrons, Matrons, and Resistance, 1899-1959 -- tChapter six. From Patronage to Populism and Back Again, 1919-26 -- tChapter seven. Revolutionary Rejection of the Patrons' Compact, 1926-33 -- tChapter eight. The Populist Compact, 1934-59 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix. Selections from the 1946 Chaparra and Delicias Collective Contract -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSugar was Cuba's principal export from the late eighteenth century throughout much of the twentieth, and during that time, the majority of the island's population depended on sugar production for its livelihood. In Blazing Cane, Gillian McGillivray examines the development of social classes linked to sugar production, and their contribution to the formation and transformation of the state, from the first Cuban Revolution for Independence in 1868 through the Cuban Revolution of 1959. She describes how cane burning became a powerful way for farmers, workers, and revolutionaries to commit sabotage, take control of the harvest season, improve working conditions, protest political repression, attack colonialism and imperialism, nationalize sugarmills, and, ultimately, acquire greater political and economic power.Focusing on sugar communities in eastern and central Cuba, McGillivray recounts how farmers and workers pushed the Cuban government to move from exclusive to inclusive politics and back again. The revolutionary caudillo networks that formed between 1895 and 1898, the farmer alliances that coalesced in the 1920s, and the working-class groups of the 1930s affected both day-to-day local politics and larger state-building efforts. Not limiting her analysis to the island, McGillivray shows that twentieth-century Cuban history reflected broader trends in the Western Hemisphere, from modernity to popular nationalism to Cold War repression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aSugarcane industryzCubaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSugarcane industryzCubaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / Cuba.2bisacsh1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391050zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391050423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/c